This paper is about unsupervised text style transfer, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). The paper proposes a novel method that uses reinforcement learning to address the challenges of weak interpretability, content preservation, and the trade-off between content and style. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also uses deep learning techniques, such as sequence-to-sequence models, which are commonly used in machine learning (ML) and artificial intelligence (AI), making cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) likely sub-categories as well. Additionally, the paper uses a mask-based inference algorithm, which involves manipulating the input data, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper uses datasets that involve text and style, which could also fall under the sub-category of computer vision (cs.CV) since text can be treated as an image.
